@page "/about"

<PageTitle>About - Elemental Utopia</PageTitle>

<div class="hero">    
    <div class="hero-content">
        <h1>Our Story</h1>
        <p>Elemental Utopia started in October 2023, on a holiday, from a single video about coffee. <br /><br/>

        At first, it wasn’t a business idea, it was curiosity. I’d just gotten a small espresso setup and a hand grinder, and what started as casual learning quickly turned into a deep dive into specialty coffee. The difference between commodity coffee and properly extracted espresso wasn’t small, it was massive. It felt like discovering that coffee wasn’t one thing, but a whole spectrum of flavour waiting to be understood.
        <br /><br/>
        That curiosity became obsession.
         <br /><br/>
        One moment that stayed with me was tasting a coffee that genuinely tasted like blueberries, bright, sweet, almost like juice in a cup. It was unexpected, almost unreal, and I’ve been chasing that kind of clarity and intensity in flavour ever since.
        <br /><br/>
        From there, the idea stopped being theoretical. I had the equipment, I had the interest, and eventually the mindset shifted to something simple: if I can do it, why wouldn’t I?
        <br /><br/>
        That mindset became the driving force behind everything. I started building, learning, failing, rebuilding. From experimenting with coffee extraction, to designing and constructing my own portable coffee setup from scratch, wood, fittings, pump, sink, finish, everything, Elemental Utopia slowly became real through iteration, not permission.
         <br /><br/>
        It’s still evolving. But it exists.</p>

        <br /><br/>
        <h1>Why we exist</h1>
        <p >Elemental Utopia exists because coffee, in its most common form, is underestimated.
        <br /><br/>
        For most people, it’s something bitter, functional, and routine, something consumed for caffeine rather than experience. But coffee, when treated with care, precision, and intention, becomes something completely different. It becomes flavour, ritual, and attention.
        <br /><br/>
        We exist to challenge the idea that coffee is supposed to be average.
        <br /><br/>
        To show that extraction, technique, and curiosity can transform something familiar into something expressive. Coffee doesn’t have to be background noise to a morning, it can be the moment you look forward to.
        <br /><br/>
        At its core, Elemental Utopia is about pushing coffee beyond convenience, and back into craft.</p>
        <br /><br/>

        <h1>What makes us different</h1>
        <p>Elemental Utopia is not a traditional coffee setup, it’s a portable, experimental coffee system.
        <br /><br/>
        It’s designed to move, adapt, and exist anywhere. A collapsible setup built to be taken into different environments rather than confined to a fixed shop. The goal is simple: remove location as a limitation on quality.
        <br /><br/>
        But what really makes it different is the approach.
        <br /><br/>
        We treat coffee like a science as much as a craft. Every cup is part of an ongoing exploration into extraction, flavour, temperature, pressure, and eventually roasting. The aim is not just consistency, it’s discovery.
        <br /><br/>
        Long term, Elemental Utopia becomes a coffee lab. A place where flavour is tested, refined, and pushed further, with the ambition of unlocking profiles that feel almost impossible, like fruit-forward espresso that carries clear notes of berries, pineapple, and beyond.
        <br /><br/>
        But it’s not just about experimentation.
        <br /><br/>
        It’s also about responsibility.
        <br /><br/>
        We care about sustainability, fair sourcing, and reducing harm in the supply chain. Coffee should not come at the cost of exploitation. Quality and ethics are not separate, they are part of the same system.
        <br /><br/>
        And finally, it’s about people.
        <br /><br/>
        We aim to build a working environment that is calm, respectful, and accessible, including sensory-aware design choices for neurodivergent staff, and a culture where employees are treated as humans first, not functions. The goal is simple: people should feel good working here, not just performing here.
        <br /><br/>
        And when someone drinks an Elemental Utopia coffee, the goal is equally simple:
        <br /><br/>
        They stop for a moment and think, “I didn’t know coffee could be like this.”</p>
